[Student "S"]
{In response to partner's Stayman bid you show your 4-card \S suit. Partner now bids 2NT.  

In response to partner's Stayman bid you show your 4-card \S suit. Partner now bids 2NT. 

Partner had \Hs, not \Ss. His 2NT bid is invitational, 9-10 points, so with 17 points you say 3NT.

North plays 3NT. East leads the \DQ.

Winner List: \S = 4 : \H = 0 : \D = 2 : \C = 2 :: Total = 8

You need one more winner. Although the \HK is a possibility, there is a real danger of losing 4 tricks in the suit if East holds the \HA.

A much better idea is to try to establish a \C trick, a suit where you hold 8 cards. 

You must give up one \C trick in order to establish a winner there. It is important that you give up that \C trick to East. West is the Danger hand because if he wins a \C he might lead through your precarious \HK. So win the first trick, enter dummy with a \S honor, and play a small \C, finessing the \C9 when West plays low.  

East wins the \CJ, but you win the game. East cannot profitably play \Hs, so he will probably continue with another \D. But since the \CQ will now drop under the \C A K you have your ninth trick.

This \C holding shows an important principle. As long as the suit splits 3-2 you can establish the fourth card as a winner by ducking one trick.

The key is your ability to choose which defender you want to duck the trick into. }
[Play "W"]DQ

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
